A compelling science fiction/dark fantasy tale that deconstructs the genre tropes associated with the era that it was based on. Is it Lovecraftian in a traditional sense? Well it's in line with genre pulp fiction of the 1920s to the 1950s in general, but it highlights the social issues that were prevalent in that era, and were overlooked in many of those stories. If anything, the real horror in this story is the racism that dominated the social atmosphere of that time, and how it impacts the characters. I believe it's a wonderful deconstruction, very meta I might say. The ending for me though, could have been much more. It's not bad, but whereas the whole story in general is great, the ending just falls short a bit. Nevertheless, it's still a great homage to the weird tales of that era.

One word to describe the film: INTENSE. Christopher Nolan brought us a very visceral and catastrophic war film that shows the sheer terror of war. This is not a heroic tale, but one of pure survival. Hans Zimmer's score induces a lot of dread. The newcomers are phenomenal, particularly Fionn Whitehead and Harry Styles (who really acts well, turns out). Is this Nolan's best film? I still prefer The Dark Knight, but this is definitely one of the best and I still find it fascinating. I have a few problems with some of the characterizations and the structure, but it's still a good war film.
8.5/10

I had doubts before about this film, given the DCEU's track record, but it actually paid off. BIG TIME. Finally, we have our first truly great DCEU film! Gal Gadot OWNED that role! The writing was great, Chris Pine was fantastic, and it has the right balance of everything! Also: COLOURS! FUN!!! This was a colorful movie! There were some flaws in the third act, but in the end, it really doesn't matter! It was awesome!

I gotta say, aside from being a great superhero film, it is also an effective socially relevant war film, one that still reflects on the world today. The choice of having it set in World War I was ingenious and thought provoking, as it is considered one of the bleakest and most morally conflicting chapters of human history. Wonder Woman is a great superhero film, not just because of its strong female protagonist, but also because of how profound its message is. In many ways it's similar to The Dark Knight, albeit more hopeful and colourful.
9.5/10

This was a terrifying return to the horror roots of the Alien franchise. I loved the Alien franchise ever since I was a very young and I thought this was a compelling addition. The production design and the effects were frightening and superb, the music was well done (glad they actually used the old themes from the first film), and Michael Fassbender was phenomenal. It's better than Prometheus, but I think the film falters a bit with the third act, and it also repeats some of the old mistakes of Prometheus. Nonetheless, it's still an engrossing science fiction horror tale with a lot of mystery and intrigue.....and plus: IT'S RATED HARD-R!!!! BALLS-TO-THE-WALL HORROR!!!!
